<div class = "travel2">
<b><p class = "trav">What is the biggest culture shock you have ever faced?</b></p>
<p>The French don't have locks on the bathroom door.

Yes. You read that right.

The first time I visited France was last May. I was going to be there for a month training with a football academy and since it was just a month, they decided the best option was for me to stay with a host family.

It would be a good experience for both parties and it would be easier as their daughter who is a year older plays for the club as well.

So on my first day, I was just getting to know the family and was figuring out how things work in their house.

At around 6 pm i realize i needed to take a shower and proceed to ask Lucy* ( She was sharing her room with me).

She lead me to the Salle de bain and explained how the tap works.

I told her i should be fine. She smiled and left.

I then closed the door and was looking for a way lock it but didn't find anything. I was pretty sure I'd made a mistake and there was some cool technology for a lock that I probably didn't know about.

So I went looking for Lucy and in my broken French asked her about the lock. She didn't understand, so we went back to the Bathroom after using Google Translate and hand gestures, I asked about the lock.

She started laughing and said, “ Oh we don't use a lock . It's for safety.”

I was stunned.

After seeing my expression, she added “Don't worry, we won't walk in on you. Just tell us before you go for a shower.”

I nodded and made a mental note, to always inform everyone in the house before I go for a shower. In India we take locks on doors pretty seriously, especially when it's the bathroom door. I can't have my dad walking in on me or anyone else for that fact.

It was uncomfortable at first and I kept looking at the door. I also took a relatively shorter time in the shower.</p>
